Note:
WebAssembly Register Allocator - Virtual Register to Wasm Local Mapping

WebAssembly has no physical registers; it uses a stack-based execution model
with indexed local variables. This file maps LIR virtual registers to Wasm
local variable indices and tracks the Wasm type (i32, i64, f32, f64) for each.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Map LIR virtual registers to Wasm local variable indices
- Track the Wasm value type for each local variable
- Manage function parameter locals (parameters are locals 0..N-1)
- Count total locals needed per function for the code section
- Support register-to-local resolution during instruction translation

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Wasm has no registers; all values live in the operand stack or local variables
- LIR uses virtual registers which must be mapped to Wasm locals
- Correct type tracking is required for Wasm validation (type-safe bytecode)
- Parameter/local separation affects the locals declaration in the code section

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Wasm local variable allocation and type tracking
- LIR virtual register to Wasm local index mapping
- Function parameter registration
- Local count and type queries for code section emission
- Type conversion from LIR types to Wasm value types

Dependencies:
- Imports LIR types for virtual register definitions
- Imports Layout for memory allocation
- Imports List for collection operations
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: WASM VALUE TYPE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
WebAssembly has four basic value types, each identified by a single byte
in the binary format. These types are used in function signatures, local
declarations, and block result types.

  0x7F = i32 (32-bit integer)
  0x7E = i64 (64-bit integer)
  0x7D = f32 (32-bit IEEE 754 float)
  0x7C = f64 (64-bit IEEE 754 float)

Additionally, funcref (0x70) and externref (0x6F) exist for reference types
but are not used in basic register allocation.
@End Reasoning

Constant WASM_TYPE_I32 as Integer is 127    Note: 0x7F
Constant WASM_TYPE_I64 as Integer is 126    Note: 0x7E
Constant WASM_TYPE_F32 as Integer is 125    Note: 0x7D
Constant WASM_TYPE_F64 as Integer is 124    Note: 0x7C
Constant WASM_TYPE_FUNCREF as Integer is 112  Note: 0x70
Constant WASM_TYPE_EXTERNREF as Integer is 111 Note: 0x6F
Constant WASM_TYPE_VOID as Integer is 64    Note: 0x40 (empty block type)

Note: Maximum locals per function (Wasm spec allows up to 2^32-1 but we cap)
Constant MAX_WASM_LOCALS as Integer is 4096

Note: ============================================================================
Note: WASM LOCAL ALLOCATION STATE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The WasmLocalAllocState tracks the mapping from LIR virtual registers to Wasm
local variable indices and their types. Wasm locals are numbered sequentially:
  locals 0..param_count-1 are the function parameters
  locals param_count..total_count-1 are the non-parameter locals

Memory layout per entry: 16 bytes
  Offset 0: LIR virtual register ID (8 bytes)
  Offset 8: Wasm value type (8 bytes)
@End Reasoning

Type called "WasmLocalAllocState":
    local_entries as Integer      Note: Pointer to array of local entries (16 bytes each)
    local_types as Integer        Note: Pointer to array of Wasm types for each local index
    lir_to_local as Integer       Note: Pointer to LIR vreg -> local index mapping
    local_count as Integer        Note: Total number of locals (params plus non-params)
    param_count as Integer        Note: Number of function parameters
    capacity as Integer           Note: Maximum number of entries allocated
End Type

Note: Size: 6 fields * 8 bytes = 48 bytes

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ALLOCATOR INITIALIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_wasm_local_alloc_state" that takes capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Creates the Wasm local allocation state with the given maximum capacity.
    Allocates three arrays:
    - local_types: maps local index -> Wasm type
    - lir_to_local: maps LIR vreg -> local index (-1 if unmapped)
    Both arrays are indexed by their respective ID spaces.
    @End Reasoning

    Let state be Layout.allocate(48)
    If state is equal to 0:
        Display "create_wasm_local_alloc_state: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let types_array be Layout.allocate(capacity multiplied by 8)
    Let mapping_array be Layout.allocate(capacity multiplied by 8)

    If types_array is equal to 0:
        Display "create_wasm_local_alloc_state: types array allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If
    If mapping_array is equal to 0:
        Display "create_wasm_local_alloc_state: mapping array allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize all mappings to -1 (unmapped)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than capacity:
        __store(types_array, i multiplied by 8, WASM_TYPE_I32)
        __store(mapping_array, i multiplied by 8, -1)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    __store(state, 0, 0)              Note: local_entries (unused, reserved)
    __store(state, 8, types_array)
    __store(state, 16, mapping_array)
    __store(state, 24, 0)             Note: local_count = 0
    __store(state, 32, 0)             Note: param_count = 0
    __store(state, 40, capacity)

    Return state
End Process

Process called "create_default_wasm_local_state" returns Integer:
    Return create_wasm_local_alloc_state(MAX_WASM_LOCALS)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PARAMETER REGISTRATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "register_parameter" that takes state as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer, wasm_type as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Registers a function parameter as a Wasm local. Parameters are assigned
    sequential local indices starting from 0. Each parameter has a known
    Wasm type from the function signature.
    Returns the assigned local index, or -1 on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    Let local_count be __load(state, 24)
    Let param_count be __load(state, 32)
    Let capacity be __load(state, 40)

    If local_count is greater than or equal to capacity:
        Display "register_parameter: capacity exceeded"
        Return -1
    End If

    Let types_array be __load(state, 8)
    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 16)

    Let local_idx be local_count

    __store(types_array, local_idx multiplied by 8, wasm_type)

    Note: Map LIR vreg to this local index
    If lir_vreg is greater than or equal to 0:
        If lir_vreg is less than capacity:
            __store(mapping_array, lir_vreg multiplied by 8, local_idx)
        End If
    End If

    __store(state, 24, local_count plus 1)
    __store(state, 32, param_count plus 1)

    Return local_idx
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOCAL ALLOCATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "map_registers_to_locals" that takes state as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer, wasm_type as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Maps a LIR virtual register to a new Wasm local variable. Assigns the
    next available local index and records the Wasm type. Non-parameter
    locals start after all parameters.
    Returns the assigned local index, or -1 on failure.
    @End Reasoning

    Let local_count be __load(state, 24)
    Let capacity be __load(state, 40)

    If local_count is greater than or equal to capacity:
        Display "map_registers_to_locals: capacity exceeded"
        Return -1
    End If

    Note: Check if this vreg is already mapped
    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 16)
    If lir_vreg is greater than or equal to 0:
        If lir_vreg is less than capacity:
            Let existing be __load(mapping_array, lir_vreg multiplied by 8)
            If existing is greater than or equal to 0:
                Return existing
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let types_array be __load(state, 8)
    Let local_idx be local_count

    __store(types_array, local_idx multiplied by 8, wasm_type)

    If lir_vreg is greater than or equal to 0:
        If lir_vreg is less than capacity:
            __store(mapping_array, lir_vreg multiplied by 8, local_idx)
        End If
    End If

    __store(state, 24, local_count plus 1)

    Return local_idx
End Process

Process called "get_local_index" that takes state as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the Wasm local index mapped to the given LIR virtual register.
    Returns -1 if the virtual register has not been mapped.
    @End Reasoning

    Let capacity be __load(state, 40)
    If lir_vreg is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If lir_vreg is greater than or equal to capacity:
        Return -1
    End If

    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 16)
    Return __load(mapping_array, lir_vreg multiplied by 8)
End Process

Process called "get_local_type" that takes state as Integer, local_idx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the Wasm value type for the given local variable index.
    Returns WASM_TYPE_I32 as default if the index is out of range.
    @End Reasoning

    Let local_count be __load(state, 24)
    If local_idx is less than 0:
        Return WASM_TYPE_I32
    End If
    If local_idx is greater than or equal to local_count:
        Return WASM_TYPE_I32
    End If

    Let types_array be __load(state, 8)
    Return __load(types_array, local_idx multiplied by 8)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: QUERY FUNCTIONS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "get_local_count" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns total number of locals (params + non-params)
    Return __load(state, 24)
End Process

Process called "get_param_count" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns number of function parameters
    Return __load(state, 32)
End Process

Process called "get_non_param_local_count" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the number of non-parameter locals. This is the count that goes
    into the code section's locals declaration (parameters are declared in
    the function type, not in the locals vector).
    @End Reasoning

    Let total be __load(state, 24)
    Let params be __load(state, 32)
    Return total minus params
End Process

Process called "get_local_type_groups" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes the number of type groups needed for the locals declaration in
    the Wasm code section. Consecutive locals of the same type are grouped
    together as (count, type) pairs. Returns the number of groups.

    For example, if non-param locals are [i32, i32, i64, i32], the groups are:
      (2, i32), (1, i64), (1, i32) = 3 groups
    @End Reasoning

    Let param_count be __load(state, 32)
    Let total_count be __load(state, 24)
    Let types_array be __load(state, 8)

    If total_count is less than or equal to param_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let group_count be 1
    Let prev_type be __load(types_array, param_count multiplied by 8)
    Let i be param_count plus 1
    While i is less than total_count:
        Let cur_type be __load(types_array, i multiplied by 8)
        If cur_type  is not equal to prev_type:
            Set group_count to group_count plus 1
            Set prev_type to cur_type
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return group_count
End Process

Process called "get_type_group_at" that takes state as Integer, group_idx as Integer, out_count as Integer, out_type as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Retrieves the count and type for a specific local type group (0-indexed).
    Writes the count to *out_count and the type to *out_type.
    Returns 1 on success, 0 if group_idx is out of range.
    @End Reasoning

    Let param_count be __load(state, 32)
    Let total_count be __load(state, 24)
    Let types_array be __load(state, 8)

    If total_count is less than or equal to param_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let current_group be 0
    Let run_start be param_count
    Let run_type be __load(types_array, param_count multiplied by 8)
    Let i be param_count plus 1

    While i is less than or equal to total_count:
        Let at_end be 0
        If i is equal to total_count:
            Set at_end to 1
        End If

        Let type_changed be 0
        If at_end is equal to 0:
            Let cur_type be __load(types_array, i multiplied by 8)
            If cur_type  is not equal to run_type:
                Set type_changed to 1
            End If
        End If

        If at_end is equal to 1:
            Set type_changed to 1
        End If

        If type_changed is equal to 1:
            If current_group is equal to group_idx:
                Let run_count be i minus run_start
                __store(out_count, 0, run_count)
                __store(out_type, 0, run_type)
                Return 1
            End If
            Set current_group to current_group plus 1
            Set run_start to i
            If at_end is equal to 0:
                Set run_type to __load(types_array, i multiplied by 8)
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TYPE CONVERSION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "lir_type_to_wasm_type" that takes lir_type as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Converts a LIR type identifier to the corresponding Wasm value type byte.
    LIR uses its own type system which must be mapped to one of the four
    Wasm primitive types.

    Mapping:
    - LIR integer types (8/16/32 bit) -> i32
    - LIR integer 64-bit -> i64
    - LIR float 32-bit -> f32
    - LIR float 64-bit -> f64
    - LIR pointer types -> i32 (in wasm32 linear memory model)
    - Default -> i32
    @End Reasoning

    Note: LIR type constants (from lir.runa)
    Note: LIR_TYPE_I8  = 1, LIR_TYPE_I16 = 2, LIR_TYPE_I32 = 3
    Note: LIR_TYPE_I64 = 4, LIR_TYPE_F32 = 5, LIR_TYPE_F64 = 6
    Note: LIR_TYPE_PTR = 7

    If lir_type is equal to 1:
        Return WASM_TYPE_I32
    End If
    If lir_type is equal to 2:
        Return WASM_TYPE_I32
    End If
    If lir_type is equal to 3:
        Return WASM_TYPE_I32
    End If
    If lir_type is equal to 4:
        Return WASM_TYPE_I64
    End If
    If lir_type is equal to 5:
        Return WASM_TYPE_F32
    End If
    If lir_type is equal to 6:
        Return WASM_TYPE_F64
    End If
    If lir_type is equal to 7:
        Return WASM_TYPE_I32
    End If
    Return WASM_TYPE_I32
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: RESET
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "reset_allocation" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Resets the allocation state for a new function. Clears all local type
    assignments and LIR-to-local mappings. Resets counts to zero.
    @End Reasoning

    Let capacity be __load(state, 40)
    Let types_array be __load(state, 8)
    Let mapping_array be __load(state, 16)

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than capacity:
        __store(types_array, i multiplied by 8, WASM_TYPE_I32)
        __store(mapping_array, i multiplied by 8, -1)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    __store(state, 24, 0)   Note: local_count = 0
    __store(state, 32, 0)   Note: param_count = 0

    Return 1
End Process
